  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Subsets\n\nReturn every subset of the given unique integers. The order of subsets is ignored.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: nums = [1,2,4]\nOutput: [[],[1],[2],[4],[1,2],[1,4],[2,4],[1,2,4]]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: nums = [0]\nOutput: [[],[0]]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: nums = []\nOutput: [[]]\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- All input values are unique.\n- Generated cases keep `nums.length` small for display.",
  "editorial": "At each index, either include the number or skip it. This forms the full powerset.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def subsets(self, nums):\n        out = []\n        def dfs(index, path):\n            if index == len(nums):\n                out.append(path[:])\n                return\n            dfs(index + 1, path)\n            path.append(nums[index])\n            dfs(index + 1, path)\n            path.pop()\n        dfs(0, [])\n        return out\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Each value has two choices: present or absent.",
    "The empty subset is always included."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def subsets(self, nums):\n        pass\n"
  },
